<HEADLINE>
Julian the Apostate Defeats the Persians; Reigns for 30 Years
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> mra...@willamette.edu </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-10-11T15:59:00 </POSTDATE>
POD:  Shapur II of Persia is one of history's great morons who refuses
to admit how military inept his is, takes personal command, and loses
battle after battle to Julian the Apostate until the Romans manage to
take the Persian capital in 363 AD.  The Roman Empire gets some more
land and Julian returns home in triumph, more secure in power than
ever thanks to a decisive victory over an ancient Roman foe.

Now what?

Well, Julian is a young man, only 32 at the time, and while he could
very well easily die in another battle or from an assassin, let's have
him live and reign until his death at the age of 62, an additional 30
years.  That's a long reign, but not that much longer than his
predecessor Constantius II.

What is the Roman Empire going to be like at this time if given a 30
year reign of a stability under a strong Emperor?

How successful will Julian's efforts at creating a more powerful pagan
church be if given 30 years to work with?

Will his efforts at splitting the Christians bear fruit?

Is he likely to be succeeded by another pagan emperor?

Thoughts?

--
Mike Ralls
</POST>
